# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: weihenstephan-standards
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Bottling lines usually include label application equipment, capping operations, date stamps, etc.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Quality assurance verification equipment is often included.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Packaging of bottled beer typically involves drawing the product from a holding tank and filling it into bottles in a filling machine (*filler*), which are then capped, labeled and packed into cases or cartons.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Many smaller breweries send their bulk beer to large facilities for contract bottling—though some will bottle by hand.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] The first step in bottling beer is *depalletising*, where the empty bottles are removed from the original pallet packaging delivered from the manufacturer, so that individual bottles may be handled.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] The bottles may then be rinsed with filtered water or air, and may have carbon dioxide injected into them in attempt to reduce the level of oxygen within the bottle.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] The bottle then enters a "filler" which fills the bottle with beer and may also inject a small amount of inert gas (usually carbon dioxide or nitrogen) on top of the beer to disperse the oxygen, as oxygen can ruin the quality of the product via oxidation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Finally, the bottles go through a "capper", which applies a bottle cap, sealing the bottle.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] A few beers are bottled with a cork and cage.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Next the bottle enters a labelling machine ("labeller") where a label is applied.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] To ensure traceability of the product, a *lot number*, generally the date and time of bottling, may also be printed on the bottle.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] The product is then packed into boxes and warehoused, ready for sale.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Depending on the magnitude of the bottling endeavor, there are many different types of bottling machinery available.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Liquid level machines fill bottles so they appear to be filled to the same line on every bottle, while volumetric filling machines fill each bottle with exactly the same amount of liquid.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Overflow pressure fillers are the most popular machines with beverage makers, while gravity filling machines are most cost effective.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] In terms of automation, inline filling machines are most popular, but rotary machines are much faster albeit much more expensive.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] The process for bottling wine is largely similar to that for bottling beer, except wine bottles differ in volumes and shapes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Traditionally, a cork is used to provide closure to wine bottles.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] After filling, a bottle travels to a corking machine (*corker*) where a cork is compressed and pushed into the neck of the bottle.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Whilst this is happening, the corker vacuums the air out of the bottle to form a negative pressure *headspace*.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] This removes any oxygen from the headspace, which is useful as latent oxygen can ruin the quality of the product via oxidation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] A negative pressure headspace will also counteract pressure caused by the thermal expansion of the wine, preventing the cork from being forced from the bottle.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Champagnes and sparkling wines may further be sealed with a muselet, which ensures the cork will not explode off in transit.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Alternative wine closures such as screw caps are available.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Some bottling lines incorporate a *fill height detector* which reject under or over-filled bottles, and also a metal detector.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] After filling and corking, a plastic or tin capsule is applied to the neck of the bottle in a *capsular*.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/bottling-line] Next the bottle enters a *labeller* where a wine label is applied.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] MES creates the "as-built" record, capturing the data, processes and outcomes of the manufacturing process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] This can be especially important in regulated industries, such as food and beverage or pharmaceutical, where documentation and proof of processes, events and actions may be required.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] As of 2025, the manufacturing execution systems are shifting from rigid, monolithic on-premise software to modular, cloud-connected platforms.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] "Manufacturing execution systems [help] create flawless manufacturing processes and provide real-time feedback of requirement changes", and provide information at a single source.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] A wide variety of systems arose using collected data for a dedicated purpose.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Further development of these systems during the 1990s introduced overlap in functionality.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Then the Manufacturing Enterprise Solutions Association International (MESA) introduced some structure by defining 11 functions that set the scope of MES.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] In 2000, the ANSI/ISA-95 standard merged this model with the Purdue Reference Model (PRM).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] A functional hierarchy was defined in which MES were situated at Level 3 between ERP at Level 4 and process control at Levels 0, 1, 2.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] With the publication of the third part of the standard in 2005, activities in Level 3 were divided over four main operations: production, quality, logistics and maintenance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Between 2005 and 2013, additional or revised parts of the ANSI/ISA-95 standard defined the architecture of an MES into more detail, covering how to internally distribute functionality and what information to exchange internally as well as externally.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Over the years, international standards and models have refined the scope of such systems in terms of activities.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] MES integrates with ISA-95 (previous Purdue Reference Model, “95”) with multiple relationships.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] The collection of systems acting on the ISA-95 Level 3 can be called manufacturing operations management systems (MOMS).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Apart from an MES, there are typically laboratory information management system (LIMS), warehouse management system (WMS) and computerized maintenance management system (CMMS).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Examples of systems acting on ISA-95 Level 4 are product lifecycle management (PLM), enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relationship management (CRM), human resource management (HRM), and process development execution system (PDES).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] In many cases, middleware enterprise application integration (EAI) systems are being used to exchange transaction messages between MES and Level 4 systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] A common data definition, B2MML, has been defined within the ISA-95 standard to link MES systems to these Level 4 systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems acting on ISA-95 Level 2 are supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA), programmable logic controllers (PLC), distributed control systems (DCS) and building automation systems (BAS).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Most MES systems include connectivity as part of their product offering.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Direct communication of plant floor equipment data is established by connecting to the PLC.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Often, plant floor data is first collected and diagnosed for real-time control in a DCS or SCADA system.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] In this case, the MES systems connect to these Level 2 systems for exchanging plant floor data.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] The industry standard for plant floor connectivity has evolved from OLE for Process Control (OPC) to OPC Unified Architecture (OPC-UA).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Unlike its predecessor, OPC-UA is platform-independent, allowing it to run on Linux and embedded devices while offering robust security models.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] In modern Industry 4.0 architectures, MES connectivity often extends beyond the traditional hierarchy.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems increasingly utilize IIoT protocols like MQTT (often with Sparkplug B) to transmit lightweight data to cloud-based analytics platforms, creating a hybrid architecture where OPC-UA handles complex machine data and MQTT handles rapid telemetry.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Measuring OEE is a manufacturing best practice.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] By measuring OEE and the underlying losses, important insights can be gained on how to systematically improve the manufacturing process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Technically, OEE is an effective metric for identifying and visualizing losses, and steering the improvement of the effectiveness of manufacturing equipment by eliminating 'waste'.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Socially, OEE can provide a common language for groups speaking in different 'languages' such as shop floor (units), managers (money) or planners (time).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The term OEE was first mentioned in Seiichi Nakajima's book 'TPM Tenkai' in 1982.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE was described as a central part of the Total Productive Maintenance methodology.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is based on the Harrington Emerson way of thinking regarding labor efficiency.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] 100% OEE is considered to be a theoretical reference point where a machine would be permanently running, at its theoretical maximal speed, producing only good products.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Anything hindering this is considered to be a 'loss'.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] When running: Is the machine running at theoretical maximal speed?
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Is the output meeting its specifications?
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The first question leads to the 'availabilty rate' of the equipment, the second one to the 'performance rate' and the third one to the 'quality rate'.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] in this way, a cascade of effectiveness and effectiveness losses arises.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The quality rate refers to a part of the performance (the part that there was 'speed', the other part is lost in the performance rate).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Performance rate refers to part of the availability (the time there was output - the other part is lost in the availability rate).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Each of the three components of the OEE points to an aspect of the process that can be targeted for improvement.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE may be applied to any individual equipment or line.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This tool also allows for drilling down for very specific analysis, such as a particular Time frame, Shift, Team or any of several other parameters.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Although the performance of a particular product can be determined from OEE data, OEE cannot be calculated for that product because this would require that all downtime (availability losses) should be correlated to specific products.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE focusses on the 'if not' in the equations: Where did potential effectiveness got lost?
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] These 'losses' of effectiveness are being subdivided further into what is known as the 'Six Big Losses' to OEE.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to make this more universally applicable and also to better reflect the financial impact of the losses, the original six big losses were later adjusted slightly.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The reason for identifying the losses in these categories is so that specific countermeasures can be applied to reduce the loss and improve the overall OEE.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Multiplying the three underlying grades AxPxQ results in a percentage value that indicates the proportion of the scheduled machine running time during which production actually met the quality criteria.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This value is always well below 100%, as 100% is a theoretical value.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Even if a system runs continuously at maximum speed without causing a single defect, it will for example still need to be serviced at some point.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Alternatively, the OEE as a number could be calculated by dividing the minimum time needed to produce the parts under optimal conditions by the actual time needed to produce the parts.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] However, in this way the losses are no longer known, meaning the most important part of OEE is missing.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The value range for OEE is between 0% and 100%.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If an effectiveness level of more than 100% is displayed, this indicates an error in the definition.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Availability portion of the OEE Metric represents the percentage of scheduled time (also referred to as 'loading time') that the equipment is available to operate.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given machine is scheduled to run for an 8-hour (480-minute) shift with a 30-minute break, during which the machine is being stopped, and there is a breakdown of 60 minutes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] During the scheduled operating time of 480 minutes, the machine was waiting 30 min. because of the break and 60 minutes because it broke down.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The performance rate represents the ratio between the theoretical maximum speed of the machine and its actual speed.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Performance can only be calculated when there is output; thus during actual running time.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] While the actual performance can be measured, it is often difficult in operational practice to obtain the theoretical maximum speed as a reference value.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The technical data provided by the machine manufacturer does not usually correspond to the theoretically possible maximum values, e.g. to avoid complaints or for other reasons.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Defining a too low maximum speed will become visible when the performance goes above 100%, which is undesirable.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Ultimately, the goal of OEE is to reveal all potential.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is a good practice to calculate the maximum value based on physical limits, e.g., a calculation of heat transfer, the power of a motor, or the fall speed of a product.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If that fails, the concept of "best demonstrated cycle time" has proven itself.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This involves determining the production speeds of products from the past and increasing the highest production speed by a margin of 20%.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Defining this as 100% performance may lead to a structurally too low OEE, however it will visualize any potential loss on the performance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The factor 1 (100%) now represents a peak value that is never exceeded, even for a short time.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For systems that only manufacture one or a few products, calculating the performance factor is simple.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If a large number of different products with different maximum speeds are run on one system (multi-product companies), the effort required to determine the maximum speed can be high and the performance should be calculated correctly using a weighted average.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given equipment is scheduled to run for an 8-hour (480-minute) and has 90 min downtime.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The equipment produces 242 Total Units during the shift.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Note: The basis is Total Units, not Good Units.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Performance metric does not penalize for Quality.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Quality portion of the OEE Metric represents the Good Units produced as a percentage of the Total Units produced.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Quality Metric is a pure measurement of Process Yield that is designed to exclude the effects of Availability and Performance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The losses due to defects and rework are called *quality losses*.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The calculations of OEE may not seem to be particularly complicated, but care must be taken as to standards that are used as the basis.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to visualize all losses, it is crucial to use the right 'configuration' of the metric.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Definitions — for parts — of the OEE can be found in ISO 22400-2:2014. and VDI 3423:2011-08 (2011) These definitions are not standardized for all industries and are individually tailored to the respective company in its application.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Furthermore, the ISO 22400 standard presents two different OEE versions that appear to be inconsistent with one another, the first of which – in the standard's normative section – contains no reference to or connection with the original Nakajima's Total Productive Maintenance (TPM) model.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To resolve this ambiguity, academic literature provides a comprehensive classification framework that maps the standard's time elements to the traditional OEE formula, ensuring consistency between the ISO standard and established industrial practices.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This to OEE dedicated standard aims for the visualisation of all effectiveness losses on any manufacturing equipment, being unabigiously clear to production personnel.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The standard uses the same logic and uniform terminology for any type of equipment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to calculate OEE, operational data needs to be acquired from the production process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This needs to reflect 'what happened' on one hand, and 'what did not happen' (the losses) on the other hand.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Depending on the systems or products, it can be difficult to collect the basic data required to determine the key figure.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Many companies therefore rely on special software for data collection.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The goal of TPM (Total Productive Maintenance) as set out by Seiichi Nakajima, is "The continuous improvement of OEE by engaging all those that impact on it in small group activities".
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To achieve this, the TPM toolbox sets out a Focused improvement tactic to reduce each of the six types of OEE loss.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For example, the Focused improvement tactic to systematically reduce breakdown risk sets out how to improve asset condition and standardise working methods to reduce human error and accelerated wear.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Zero Failure Management provides a profound structure to achieve this.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Combining OEE with Focused improvement converts OEE from a lagging to a leading indicator that can be used to guide performance management priorities.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The first Focused improvement stage of OEE improvement is to achieve a stable OEE, i.e. one which varies at around 5% from the mean for a representative production sample.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This indicates that the asset performance is stable and not affected by variability in equipment wear rates and working methods.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The second stage of OEE improvement (optimisation) is meant to remove chronic losses.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] As the TPM process delivers these gains through small cross functional improvement teams, the process of OEE improvement should also raise front line team engagement, problem ownership, collaboration and skill levels.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This combination of OEE as a KPI, TPM Focused improvement tactics and front line team engagement is intended to make the gains sustainable and deliver the TPM goal of year on year improvement in OEE.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Zero Failure Management helps significantly to achieve this.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE measurement is also commonly used as a key performance indicator (KPI) in conjunction with lean manufacturing efforts.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To achieve the main goal of Lean, creating flow, individual pieces of equipment need to be fully reliable and in tune.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] TEEP, therefore, reports the 'bottom line' effectiveness of manufacturing equipment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To calculate the Total Effective Equipment Performance(TEEP), the OEE is multiplied by a fourth component: Loading.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Loading rate of the TEEP Metric represents the percentage of time that the equipment is scheduled to operate compared to the total Calendar Time that is available.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Loading Metric is a pure measurement of Schedule effectiveness and is designed to exclude the effects how well that equipment may perform.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given equipment is scheduled to run 5 Days per Week, 24 Hours per Day.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For a given week, the Total Calendar Time is 7 Days at 24 Hours.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The advantage of OEE lies in the transparency of the value added share and the associated losses of the equipment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The term "Overall Equipment Efficiency" is often wrongly used as a synonym for "Overall Equipment Effectiveness".
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Measures that increase production output but incur disproportionately high costs may well be effective, but at the same time they may be inefficient and therefore economically unviable and thus unproductive.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Often, insufficient quality is not detected at the equipment that caused it.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In this case, it has proven effective to apply the "discovery principle," i.e., to apply an OEE reduction to the equipment where the error was discovered.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This removes the OEE from being purely equipment-related and turns it into a process indicator.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] However, the OEE of a piece of equipment can of course also be optimized by making improvements to other equipment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The OEE should also be a key figure that is as up-to-date as possible.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In this respect, the OK quantity should be determined at the latest at the end of the shift and the OEE calculated.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] From the perspective of Process Control, the question rises how an operator can be responsible for manufacturing correct products if he cannot see whether the products are correct.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To highlight this problem, it is worth considering blocked products as a quality issue: after all, they were not right the first time around.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Valuable activities such as setup or maintenance will also reduce overall equipment effectiveness (OEE) at the beginning.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If setup activities reduce overall equipment effectiveness, there is an incentive to reduce setup times using SMED (Single-minute exchange of die).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] On the other hand, this also means that OEE can be increased by reducing the number of changeovers, i.e. by increasing batch sizes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This would contradict the principles of lean production.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This highlights the importance of a clear explanation of OEE: the goal is not to be as high as possible, but to identify obstacles and then eliminate them.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A convention must be agreed within the company to define when downtime occurs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Recording and justifying every second of equipment downtime is too time-consuming for most companies.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In practice, a recording limit of 1 to 5 minutes of equipment downtime has proven to be a pragmatic approach.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] All downtimes of less than one minute are therefore included in the performance rate.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The collected data must be processed in order to obtain meaningful information.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This information is aimed at various target groups, such as.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Meaningful analyses prove to be the key to good decisions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Theoretically, this is only possible with very precise figures.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In practice, it has been shown that correctly selected data has a greater effect in this respect than high precision.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Although tempting, OEE (as a number) is NOT suitable for comparing machines or benchmarking.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For similar reasons, OEE may not be applied to aggregate to Department or Plant levels.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Where multiple machines are linked together, each individual piece of equipment will display the waiting categories "No Input" (Starved) and "No output" (Blocked) in addition to the standard standstill reasons.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This allows upstream or downstream faults in production equipment to be identified.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The use of OEE requires knowledge of manufacturing environments and understanding of the underlying data.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Without this, a specific OEE number may be of little to no value.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE cannot be used to measure employee performance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is used to identify and measure equipment losses, which can then be eliminated through appropriate root cause analysis and measures.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Using OEE as a heuristic is not recommended.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O), in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] They can be designed for many arrangements of digital and analog I/O, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs were first developed in the automobile manufacturing industry to provide flexible, rugged and easily programmable controllers to replace hard-wired relay logic systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Dick Morley, who invented the first PLC, the Modicon 084, for General Motors in 1968, is considered the father of PLC.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an example of a hard real-time system since output results must be produced in response to input conditions within a limited time, otherwise unintended operation may result.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC originated in the late 1960s in the automotive industry in the US and was designed to replace relay logic systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Before, control logic for manufacturing was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The hard-wired nature of these components made it difficult for design engineers to alter the automation process.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Changes would require rewiring and careful updating of the documentation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] When general-purpose computers became available, they were soon applied to control logic in industrial processes.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] These early computers were unreliable and required specialist programmers and strict control of working conditions, such as temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC provided several advantages over earlier automation systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] It was designed to tolerate the industrial environment better than systems intended for office use, and was more reliable, compact, and required less maintenance than relay systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] It was easily expandable with additional I/O modules.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] While relay systems required tedious and sometimes complicated hardware changes in case of reconfiguration, a PLC can be reconfigured by loading new or modified code.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] This allowed for easier iteration over manufacturing process design.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] With a simple programming language focused on logic and switching operations, it was more user-friendly than computers using general-purpose programming languages.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Early PLCs were programmed in ladder logic, which strongly resembled a schematic diagram of relay logic.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] It also permitted its operation to be monitored.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In recent years, the introduction of virtual PLCs has expanded the scope of programmable logic controllers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Virtual PLCs are software-based controllers that simulate the functions of traditional PLCs but are executed on general-purpose hardware, offering a more cost-effective and flexible alternative.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] These controllers enable automation systems to be managed without the need for dedicated hardware, making them ideal for applications requiring simulation, remote control, or cloud-based systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In 1968, GM Hydramatic, the automatic transmission division of General Motors, issued a request for proposals for an electronic replacement for hard-wired relay systems based on a white paper written by engineer Edward R.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The winning proposal came from Bedford Associates from Bedford, Massachusetts.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The result, built in 1969, was the first PLC and designated the *084*, because it was Bedford Associates' eighty-fourth project.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Bedford Associates started a company, **Modicon, Inc.**, dedicated to developing, manufacturing, selling, and servicing this new product, which they named **Modicon** (standing for "modular digital controller").
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] One of the people who worked on that project was Dick Morley, who is considered to be the father of the PLC.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The Modicon brand was sold in 1977 to Gould Electronics and later to Schneider Electric, its current owner.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] About this same time, Modicon created Modbus, a data communications protocol to be used with its PLCs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Modbus has since become a standard open protocol commonly used to connect many industrial electrical devices.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] One of the first Modicon 084 models built is now on display at Schneider Electric's facility in North Andover, Massachusetts.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] It was presented to Modicon by GM, when the unit was retired after nearly twenty years of uninterrupted service.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Modicon used the 84 moniker at the end of its product range like Modicon Micro 84 and Modicon TSX CSY 84 until after the 984 made its appearance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In a parallel development, Odo Josef Struger is sometimes known as the "father of the programmable logic controller" as well.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] He was involved in the invention of the Allen-Bradley programmable logic controller.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the release of the IBM "Personal Computer" in 1981, these devices were commonly known simply as "Programmable Controllers", or "PC's.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] But rapid expansion of the personal computer industry in the early 1980's, the abbreviation "PC" was rapidly and universally accepted as a reference to "Personal Computers".
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Odo was later credited with coining the "PLC" acronym to distinguish these two technologies, And the inclusion of the word "Logic" was an easy choice as "Ladder Logic" had already been accepted as the name of the programming language.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley (now a brand owned by Rockwell Automation) went on to become the dominant PLC manufacturer in the United States during his tenure.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Struger played a leadership role in developing IEC 61131-3 PLC programming language standards.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley's PLC-5 family, preceded by the 1774-PLC (released in the 1980's, was the first modular design found in modern-day systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] While Modicon was the most popular of the first full featured PLC's through the early 1980's, Allen Bradley overtook them in the mid-1980's and grew to own the largest market share of PLC hardware and software in North America.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Many early PLC programming applications were not capable of graphical representation of the logic, and so it was instead represented as a series of logic expressions in some kind of Boolean format, similar to Boolean algebra.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] As programming terminals evolved, because ladder logic was a familiar format used for electro-mechanical control panels, it became more commonly used.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Newer formats, such as state logic, function block diagrams, and structured text exist.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Ladder logic remains popular because PLCs solve the logic in a predictable and repeating sequence, and ladder logic allows the person writing the logic to see any issues with the timing of the logic sequence more easily than would be possible in other formats.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Up to the mid-1990s, PLCs were programmed using proprietary programming panels or special-purpose programming terminals, which often had dedicated function keys representing the various logical elements of PLC programs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Some proprietary programming terminals displayed the elements of PLC programs as graphic symbols, but plain ASCII character representations of contacts, coils, and wires were common.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Programs were stored on cassette tape cartridges.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Facilities for printing and documentation were minimal due to a lack of memory capacity.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The oldest PLCs used magnetic-core memory.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an industrial microprocessor-based controller with programmable memory used to store program instructions and various functions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs require a programming device that is used to develop and later download the created program into the memory of the controller.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs generally contain a real-time operating system, such as OS-9 or VxWorks.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] There are two types of mechanical design for PLC systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] A *single box* (also called a *brick*) is a small programmable controller that fits all units and interfaces into one compact casing, although, typically, additional expansion modules for inputs and outputs are available.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The second design type – a *modular* PLC – has a chassis (also called a *rack*) that provides space for modules with different functions, such as power supply, processor, selection of I/O modules and communication interfaces – which all can be customized for the particular application.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Several racks can be administered by a single processor and may have thousands of inputs and outputs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Either a special high-speed serial I/O link or comparable communication method is used so that racks can be distributed away from the processor, reducing the wiring costs for large plants.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Discrete (digital) signals can only take *on* or *off* value (1 or 0, *true* or *false*).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Examples of devices providing a discrete signal include limit switches and photoelectric sensors.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Analog signals can use voltage or current that is analogous to the monitored variable and can take any value within their scale.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Pressure, temperature, flow, and weight are often represented by analog signals.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically interpreted as integer values with various ranges of accuracy depending on the device and the number of bits available to store the data.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] For example, an analog 0 to 10 V or 4-20 mA current loop input would be converted into an integer value of 0 to 32,767.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC will take this value and translate it into the desired units of the process so the operator or program can read it.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Some special processes need to work permanently with minimum unwanted downtime.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Therefore, it is necessary to design a system that is fault tolerant.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In such cases, to increase the system availability in the event of hardware component failure, redundant CPU or I/O modules with the same functionality can be added to a hardware configuration to prevent a total or partial process shutdown due to hardware failure.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Other redundancy scenarios could be related to safety-critical processes, for example, large hydraulic presses could require that two PLCs turn on an output before the press can come down in case one PLC does not behave properly.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Programmable logic controllers are intended to be used by engineers without a programming background.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] For this reason, a graphical programming language called ladder logic was first developed.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] It resembles the schematic diagram of a system built with electromechanical relays and was adopted by many manufacturers and later standardized in the IEC 61131-3 control systems programming standard.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, it is still widely used, thanks to its simplicity.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, the majority of PLC systems adhere to the IEC 61131-3 standard that defines two textual programming languages: Structured Text (similar to Pascal) and Instruction List; as well as three graphical languages: ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Instruction List was deprecated in the third edition of the standard.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs can be programmed in a variety of ways, from the relay-derived ladder logic to programming languages such as specially adapted dialects of BASIC and C.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] While the fundamental concepts of PLC programming are common to all manufacturers, differences in I/O addressing, memory organization, and instruction sets mean that PLC programs are never perfectly interchangeable between different makers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Even within the same product line of a single manufacturer, different models may not be directly compatible.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Manufacturers develop programming software for their PLCs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In addition to being able to program PLCs in multiple languages, they provide common features like hardware diagnostics and maintenance, software debugging, and offline simulation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLC programs are typically written in a programming device, which can take the form of a desktop console, special software on a personal computer, or a handheld device.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The program is then downloaded to the PLC through a cable connection or over a network.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] It is stored either in non-volatile flash memory or battery-backed-up RAM on the PLC.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In some PLCs, the program is transferred from the programming device using a programming board that writes the program into a removable chip, such as EPROM, that is then inserted into the PLC.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] An incorrectly programmed PLC can result in lost productivity and dangerous conditions for programmed equipment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLC simulation is a feature often found in PLC programming software.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] It allows for testing and debugging early in a project's development.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Testing the project in simulation improves its quality, increases the level of safety associated with equipment and can save time during the installation and commissioning of automated control applications since many scenarios can be tried and tested before the system is activated.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The main difference compared to most other computing devices is that PLCs are intended for and therefore tolerant of more severe environmental conditions (such as dust, moisture, heat, cold), while offering extensive input/output (I/O) to connect the PLC to sensors and actuators.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLC input can include simple digital elements such as limit switches, analog variables from process sensors (such as temperature and pressure), and more complex data such as that from positioning or machine vision systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLC output can include elements such as indicator lamps, sirens, electric motors, pneumatic or hydraulic cylinders, magnetic relays, solenoids, or analog outputs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The input/output arrangements may be built into a simple PLC, or the PLC may have external I/O modules attached to a fieldbus or computer network that plugs into the PLC.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The functionality of the PLC has evolved over the years to include sequential relay control, motion control, process control, distributed control systems, and networking.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The data handling, storage, processing power, and communication capabilities of some modern PLCs are approximately equivalent to desktop computers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLC-like programming combined with remote I/O hardware allows a general-purpose desktop computer to serve as a PLC in certain applications.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The most basic function of a programmable logic controller is to emulate the functions of electromechanical relays.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Within the PLC programming environment, discrete inputs are given a unique address, and a PLC instruction can test if the input state is on or off.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Just as a series of relay contacts performs a logical AND function, not allowing current to pass unless all the contacts are closed, so a series of *examine if on* instructions will energize its output storage bit if all the input bits are on.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Similarly, a parallel set of instructions will perform a logical OR.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In an electromechanical relay wiring diagram, a group of contacts controlling one coil is called a *rung* of a *ladder diagram*, and this concept is also used to describe PLC logic.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The output of each rung sets or clears a storage bit, which may be associated with a discrete output or which may be an *internal coil* with no physical connection.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Such internal coils can be used, for example, as a common element in multiple separate rungs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] More advanced instructions of the PLC may be implemented as functional blocks, which carry out some operation, such as manipulating an internal variable, when enabled by a logical input and which produce outputs to signal, for example, completion or errors.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs use built-in ports, such as USB, Ethernet, RS-232, RS-485, or RS-422 to communicate with external devices (sensors, actuators) and systems (programming tools, SCADA and other user interfaces).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Communication is carried over various industrial network protocols, like Modbus, or EtherNet/IP.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Many of these protocols are vendor specific.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Formerly, some manufacturers offered dedicated communication modules as an add-on function where the processor had no network connection built in.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs used in larger I/O systems may have peer-to-peer (P2P) communication between processors.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] This allows separate parts of a complex process to have individual control while allowing the subsystems to coordinate over the communication link.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs may need to interact with people for the purpose of configuration, alarm reporting, or everyday control.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] A human-machine interface (HMI) is employed for this purpose.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] HMIs are also referred to as man-machine interfaces (MMIs) and graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] A simple system may use buttons and lights to interact with the user.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Text displays are available as well as graphical touch screens.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] More complex systems use programming and monitoring software installed on a computer, with the PLC connected via a communication interface.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC works in a program scan cycle, where it executes its program repeatedly.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The program follows the sequence of instructions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] It typically takes a time span of tens of milliseconds for the processor to evaluate all the instructions and update the status of all outputs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] If the system contains remote I/O—for example, an external rack with I/O modules—then that introduces additional uncertainty in the response time of the PLC system.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Special-purpose I/O modules may be used where the scan time of the PLC is too long to allow predictable performance.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Precision timing modules, or counter modules for use with shaft encoders, are used where the scan time would be too long to reliably count pulses or detect the sense of rotation of an encoder.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] This allows even a relatively slow PLC to still interpret the counted values to control a machine, as the accumulation of pulses is done by a dedicated module that is unaffected by the speed of program execution.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] As PLCs became more advanced, methods were developed to change the sequence of ladder execution, and subroutines were implemented.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the discovery of the Stuxnet computer worm in June 2010, the security of PLCs received little attention.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Modern programmable controllers generally contain real-time operating systems, which can be vulnerable to exploits in a similar way as desktop operating systems.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can also be attacked by gaining control of a computer they communicate with.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Since 2011, these concerns have grown as networking is becoming more commonplace in the PLC environment, connecting the previously separated plant floor networks and office networks.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In February 2021, Rockwell Automation publicly disclosed a critical vulnerability affecting its Logix controller family.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The secret cryptographic key used to verify communication between the PLC and workstation could be extracted from the programming software (Studio 5000 Logix Designer) and used to remotely change program code and configuration of a connected controller.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The vulnerability was given a severity score of 10 out of 10 on the Common Vulnerability Scoring System.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Safety PLCs can be either a standalone device or safety-rated hardware and functionality added to existing controller architectures (Allen-Bradley GuardLogix, Siemens F-series, etc.).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] These differ from conventional PLC types by being suitable for safety-critical applications for which PLCs have traditionally been supplemented with hard-wired safety relays and areas of the memory dedicated to the safety instructions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The standard of safety level is the safety integrity level (SIL).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] A safety PLC might be used to control access to a robot cell with trapped-key access, or to manage the shutdown response to an emergency stop button on a conveyor production line.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Such PLCs typically have a restricted regular instruction set augmented with safety-specific instructions designed to interface with emergency stop buttons, light screens, and other safety-related devices.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs are well adapted to a range of automation tasks.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically industrial processes in manufacturing where the cost of developing and maintaining the automation system is high relative to the total cost of the automation system, and where changes to the system would be expected during its operational life.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs contain input and output devices compatible with industrial devices and controls; little electrical design is required, and the design problem centers on expressing the desired sequence of operations.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] PLC applications are typically highly customized systems, so the cost of a packaged PLC is low compared to the cost of a specific custom-built controller design.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] On the other hand, in the case of mass-produced goods, customized control systems are economical.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] This is due to the lower cost of the components, which can be optimally chosen instead of a *generic* solution, and where the non-recurring engineering charges are spread over thousands or millions of units.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] These are for small machines and systems with low or medium volume.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] They can execute PLC languages such as ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] They are similar to traditional PLCs, but their small size allows developers to design them into custom printed circuit boards like a microcontroller, without computer programming knowledge, but with a language that is easy to use, modify and maintain.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Architecturally, they sit between the classic PLC or micro-PLC and microcontrollers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Automotive applications are an example; millions of units are built each year, and very few end-users alter the programming of these controllers.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] However, some specialty vehicles, such as transit buses, economically use PLCs instead of custom-designed controllers, because the volumes are low and the development cost would be uneconomical.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Very complex process control, such as that used in the chemical industry, may require algorithms and performance beyond the capability of even high-performance PLCs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Very high-speed or precision controls may also require customized solutions; for example, aircraft flight controls.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Single-board computers using semi-customized or fully proprietary hardware may be chosen for very demanding control applications where the high development and maintenance cost can be supported.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] **Soft PLCs** running on desktop-type computers can interface with industrial I/O hardware while executing programs within a version of commercial operating systems adapted for process control needs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] The rising popularity of single-board computers has also had an influence on the development of PLCs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Traditional PLCs are generally closed platforms, but some newer PLCs (e.g., groov EPIC from Opto 22, ctrlX from Bosch Rexroth, PFC200 from Wago, PLCnext from Phoenix Contact, and Revolution Pi from Kunbus) provide the features of traditional PLCs on an open platform.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In more recent years, small products called programmable logic relays (PLRs) or smart relays have become more common and accepted.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] These are similar to PLCs and are used in light industries where only a few points of I/O are needed, and low cost is desired.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] These small devices are typically made in a common physical size and shape by several manufacturers and branded by the makers of larger PLCs to fill their low-end product range.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Most of these have 8 to 12 discrete inputs, 4 to 8 discrete outputs, and up to 2 analog inputs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Most have an RS-232 or RS-485 port for connecting to a PC so that programmers can use user-friendly software for programming instead of the small LCD and push-button set for this purpose.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike regular PLCs that are usually modular and greatly expandable, the PLRs are usually not modular or expandable, but their cost can be significantly lower than that a PLC, and they still offer robust design and deterministic execution of the logic.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] A variant of PLCs, used in remote locations, is the remote terminal unit or RTU.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] An RTU is typically a low power, ruggedized PLC whose key function is to manage the communications links between the site and the central control system (typically SCADA) or in some modern systems, "The Cloud".
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike factory automation using wired communication protocols such as Ethernet, communications links to remote sites are often radio-based and are less reliable.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] To account for the reduced reliability, RTU will buffer messages or switch to alternate communications paths.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] When buffering messages, the RTU will timestamp each message so that a full history of site events can be reconstructed.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] RTUs, being PLCs, have a wide range of I/O and are fully programmable, typically with languages from the IEC 61131-3 standard that is common to many PLCs, RTUs and DCSs.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] In remote locations, it is common to use an RTU as a gateway for a PLC, where the PLC is performing all site control and the RTU is managing communications, time-stamping events and monitoring ancillary equipment.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/programmable-logic-controller] On sites with only a handful of I/O, the RTU may also be the site PLC and will perform both communications and control functions.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] The **Weihenstephan Standards** ("Weihenstephaner Standard" in German), also referred to as "WS" in shorthand, are communication interfaces for machine data acquisition.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] The standards were developed by a working group of machine manufacturers, plant suppliers, IT system vendors and technologists, under the guidance of the Technical University of Munich (TUM) at the Faculty of Food Packaging Technology in Weihenstephan, Germany.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] Weihenstephan libraries have been developed for production data acquisition in bottling and packaging plants (WS Pack), food industry plants (WS Food), in the bakery industry (WS Bake), and for processes within the brewing industry (WS Brew).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] These libraries are used to connect the plants industrial equipment within the production processes to higher-level management and control systems such as data acquisition systems (SCADA) or Manufacturing Execution Systems (MES).
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] In the Weihenstephan Standards, the physical interface specification, specification of the interface content, recommendations for data evaluation and reporting are defined.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] The Weihenstephan Standards 2000 comprise the guidelines for standard BDE specifications for bottling plants; the Weihenstephan Standards 2005 describe the interfaces and data provision for bottling and packaging plants in the beverage industry.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] The Weihenstephan standards are located in the automation pyramid as a link between the production management level and the process control level.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] The standards allow an MES to exchange data with the controls of various machines and thus support the MES' operation.
[src:weihenstephan-standards/weihenstephan-standards] In addition, industry-specific reports and evaluation examples are available in the Weihenstephan Standards.
